<h3>Content</h3>
<pre>
********************************************************************************
// SECTION 3 REGRESSION 2
********************************************************************************


// Exercise 1 {US Current Population Survey Data}


**********************************************
webuse "cpso8.dta",clear
// 1. Estimate the equation
reg ahe female
est store model1
* The wage differential is significant.
* The t-value is large (and negative)
* The p-value is 0
* The wage for females is significantly lower than that of males

// 2. Control for additional factors
reg ahe female bachelor age
est store model2
* Females still earn less than males under this model. In fact, the differential is even larger!
* Marital status and age are also significant.

// 3. Nonlinearities
// The results frome estimating the previous model suggest that the older a person is, the higher his/her wage is.
// Why should this be the case? Surely wage does not have a linear relationship with age.
// Create age^2 variable
qui g	age2	=	age^2
reg ahe female bachelor age age2
est store model3

est table model1 model2 model3, star title("Wage differential")
* The difference in wages between the genders is similar in magnitude to the model in part (2). The coefficient is significant.
* The difference in wages between single and married individuals is significant, and similar in magnitude to model (2)
* The age factor in wages (linear and nonlinear components) is no longer significant in model (3).


**********************************************


// Exercise 2 {Electricity Data}


**********************************************
webuse "elecex.dta", clear
g date	=	tq(1972q2)+_n-1
tsset date, quarterly

// Generate required variables
g lkwh		=	log(reskwh/nocust)			// The dependent variable
g ly		=	log((100*income)/(cpi*pop))	// Real per capita income
g lprice	=	log(100*price/cpi)			// Real average cost of electricity

// 1. Estimate base model of demand on price, income and weather
reg lkwh ly lprice cdd hdd

// 2. Check the signs
* Expect income to have positive correlation					-	Estimate gives negative correlation
* Expect price/cost to have negative correlation				-	As expected
* Expect both weather conditions to have positive correlation	-	As expected

// 3. Test for autocorrelation
estat bgodfrey, lags(1)
* There is autocorrelation in the first order

// Cochrane-Orcutt procedure by means of Prais-Winston technique
prais lkwh ly lprice cdd hdd, corc
// Now the estimates are as expected!


**********************************************


// Exercise 3 {CEO Salaries}


**********************************************
webuse "ceosal2.dta", clear

// 1. Estimate
reg lsalary lsales lmktval ceoten
est store model1
predict double lsalaryhat, xb

// 2.
g m	=	exp(lsalaryhat)

// 3. Compute alpha
reg salary m, nocons
// alpha = 1.1169


**********************************************


// Exercise 4 {California Schools Data}


**********************************************
webuse "caschool.dta",clear
// 1. Run the regression
reg testscr str					// Model 1
est store model1

// 2. Regress Model 2
reg testscr str el_pct			// Model 2
* Coefficient of "str" was -2.279808. It is now -1.101296.
est store model2

// 3. Regress Model 3
reg testscr str el_pct expn_stu	//Model 3
est store model3

// 4. Summarise the coefficients and standard errors
est table model1 model2 model3, se title("Test scores")
* The best way to summarise the outputs in a way that makes them easily comparable is to tabulate the estimates.

// 5. Test hypothesis
test _b[str]=_b[expn_stu]=0
* or -test str expn_stu-
* Both methods produce the same result, which is that
	* the null hypothesis of both coefficients being zero is rejected,
	* i.e. at least one of the two is significantly different from zero.


**********************************************


// Exercise 5 {Food Data}


**********************************************
webuse "food.dta", clear

// 1. Estimate linear model
reg food_exp income
// Check residuals for heteroskedasticity
imtest, white
* Residuals are heteroskedastic at 5% significance level (p-val=2.29%)

// 2. Corrected standard errors
reg food_exp income, vce(robust)
* Point estimates are the same.

// 3. Compute elasticity
// (I)	Manually
// Elasticity	=	([percentage change in expenditure]/[percentage change in income])x([income]/[expenditure])
// 				=	[slope of line] x ([income]/[expenditure])
* Store coefficient of income (slope of line)
g slope		=	_b[income]
* Say we want elasticity at the mean.
* Store values of mean of income and mean of predicted dependent variable.
sum income
g mincome	=	r(mean)
predict double y, xb
sum y
g my		=	r(mean)
// Compute elasticity
display slope*mincome/my

// (II)	Using mfx command
mfx compute, eyex at(mean)


**********************************************


// Exercise 6 {Nonlinear Consumption Function}


**********************************************
webuse "usdata.dta", clear
g dates	=	tq(1960q1)+_n-1
tsset dates, quarterly

// Estimate nonlinear model
nl (con={b0}+{b1=0.5}*inc^{b2=1})
* Estimates are the same as in the question. Verified.
nl (con={b0}+{b1}*inc^{b2})
* Without starting values for {b1} and {b2}, the estimates are completely different.

</pre>
